b'' b'accounts of anti-armenian human rights violations in azerbaijan b'prelude to current events in nagorno-karabakh' b'' b'' b'+--------------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'| b'| they grab papa, carry him into one room, and mamma and me into another. b'| they put mamma on the bed and start undressing her, beating her legs. b"| they start tearing my clothes, right there, in front of mamma. i don't b'| remember where they went, what they did, or how much time passed. i had b'| the feeling that they beat me on the head, on my body, and tore my b"| clothes, all at the same time, i don't even know what i said. the b'| atrocities started. i was savagely raped in that room. they argued among b'| themselves who would go first. b'| b'+--------------------------------------------------------------------------+' b'' b'' b'deposition of karine (karina) grigorevna m. b'' b'born b'secretary-typist' b'azsantekmontazh trust' b'sumgait construction and installation administration' b'secretary of the smu komsomol organization' b'' b'resident at building 17/33b, apartment b'microdistrict no. b'sumgait [azerbaijan]' b'' b'' b"on the 27th my sister marina and i went to the movies the seven o'clock show," b'at the theater that is across from the city party committee, about yards' b'away. the sk theater. they were showing an argentinian film, "the abyss."' b'before the film we noticed about to people standing near the podium at' b"the city party committee, but they were silent, there's no conversation" b"whatsoever, and we couldn't figure out what was going on. that is, we knew it" b'was about karabagh, but what it was exactly, what they were talking about, if' b"someone gave a speech or not, we didn't know. we bought our tickets. there" b'were or people in the theater. this was a very small number for that' b'large movie theater. the film started. about minutes later they stopped the' b'film. a crowd burst in. about people. they came up onto the stage. well' b'mostly they were young people, from to years old. they demanded that an' b'armenian woman come up onto the stage. they used foul language and said that' b'they were going to show what azerbaijanis were capable of, what they could do' b"to armenian girls. i thought that's what they meant because they had demanded" b'a girl specifically. marina and i were sitting together. i told her to move' b'over, there were some russian girls sitting nearby. so that if someone' b'recognized me or if something happened, they would take me, and not marina.' b"it got quiet, or girls jumped up to run out, but the door was closed--it's" b'only opened at the end of the show--and they returned to their seats.' b'everyone in the theater was looking at one another, russians, azerbaijanis,' b'people of various nationalities. but no one reacted at all, no one in the' b'auditorium made a sound. they were silent, looking at one another, and' b'gradually started to leave. some guy, a really fat one, says, "ok, we\'ve' b'scared them enough, let\'s leave." they leave slowly, pompously. it seemed to' b'me that those people were not themselves. either they had smoked a bunch of' b'"anasha", or had taken something else, because they all looked beastly, like' b'they were ready to tear anyone apart. then it was all over, as though nothing' b'had happened at all. the film started up again, it was one of those cheerful' b'films which should have only brought pleasure, made you happy to be alive. we' b'could barely sit to the end. so it had started at seven it was over by nine,' b'and it was dark b'' b"marina and i were walking home, lenin street, that's the center of town. lenin" b'street was packed, just packed with young people. they were shouting,' b"something about karabagh and something about armenians. we weren't especially" b"listening, because the way we were feeling we didn't know if we were going to" b'make it home or not, and just what had happened anyway? public transportation' b"wasn't running. incidentally, when we came out of the theater we saw police," b'policemen standing there. the director of the movie theater was looking at the' b'doors, because when they were leaving they had broken the glass, the doors' b'there are basically all glass. everything was broken. he stood there grief-' b'stricken, but looking as though nothing really big had happened, like some' b'naughty boys had just broken them quite by accident, with a slingshot. well,' b'since he looked more or less calm i decided that, nothing all that super' b'serious had happened. we went out very slowly; we wanted to catch a bus, we' b"live literally one stop away. we didn't want to go on foot, not because it was" b'dark, but because something might happen. we flagged down a cab, but the' b"driver didn't want to take us. we told him we live near the bus station, and" b"he said he'd take us to the bus station and not a yard farther. i said, well," b'ok b'' b'so we got into the cab and managed to get there. something incredible was' b'happening at the bus station. there was a traffic jam. public transportation' b'was at a standstill and everyone was shouting "ka-ra-bagh," they\'re not going' b"to give up karabagh. i go home and tell my family what's going on, and there's" b'immediate panic in the house. mamma says, what should we do? like the end had' b"come, they were going to come, kill us, that's it somehow we managed to" b'cheer ourselves up: nothing that bad could happen. where are we living anyway,' b'just what kind of social order do we have? somehow we manage to calm mamma' b'down. and we went to bed. but no one could sleep. everyone made as though' b'nothing had happened.' b'' b"that was on saturday. in short, the day went by. we didn't go anywhere and" b"didn't call our relatives. no one did anything. because life goes on." b"that day i realized something was approaching, but what exactly, i couldn't" b'guess.' b'' b'on the 28th everything was like it was supposed to be, we lived like we always' b'had. there were five of us at home: mamma, papa and us, three sisters: lyuda,' b'marina, and i. my sister lyuda was in yerevan at the time. we sat at home and' b'no one went out. later we learned that a demonstration had started that' b'morning. it all started they were smashing up stores. we were sitting at' b"home and didn't know anything about it. then a girlfriend of mine, lyuda" b"zimogliad, came by at around three o'clock i think. we worked together, we did" b"our apprenticeships together, she's a russian girl. she said that something" b'awful was happening in town. i asked, "don\'t they want armenians? well what' b'are they after, if they\'re already in that state?" she says, no, nothing like' b"that, it's just a demonstration, but it's awful to watch it. somehow, it feels" b'like a war has broken out. public transportation has been stopped the' b"cabs, the buses, well it's just a nightmare." b'' b'then papa decides to go to the drugstore, my mother was having allergy' b'problems at the time he left the house and our neighbor, aunt vera,' b'asked him, "where are you going? stop! there are such terrible things going' b'on in the courtyard; aren\'t you afraid to go out?" papa didn\'t know what she' b'was talking about. she simply pushed him back into the entryway. he came home' b'and told mamma. mamma said, "well, if aunt vera was talking like that it means' b'that something is really going on." but we didn\'t go see her, she\'s a russian,' b"she lives across from us. i had to see my friend out. around five o'clock i" b'tell lyuda, "ok, look, it\'s time for you to go, it\'s late already, i\'ll see' b'you out." mamma says, "you don\'t need to go, it\'s too late already, you can' b'see what the situation in town is." so we decided to stay home. dinner was' b'ready. mamma says, "let her eat with us, then she can go." we sat down at the' b'table. but no one was hungry, no one was in the mood, we just put everything' b"out on the table to calm ourselves down, and make it appear that we're eating." b'we turned on the television, and the show "in fairy-tale land" was coming on.' b'we cleared the table.' b'' b"we hear some noise out in the courtyard. i go out on the balcony, but i can't" b"see what's going on, because the noise is coming from the direction of the bus" b'station, and there is a 9-story building in the way. there is mob of people' b". i can't figure out what's happening. they're shouting something, looking" b"somewhere, i can't make out what is going on. i go down to a neighbor, she's" b"an azerbaijani; we've been friends of her family for about years. i go down" b'to look from their place. i see people shouting, looking at the 5-and 9-story' b'buildings near the bus station. just then soldiers set upon them, about b'people, with clubs. the mob runs off in different directions. i even see' b'several people from our building. they are looking and laughing i decide' b"that means it's not all that bad if they are laughing: it means they're not" b'killing anyone. but now the crowd suddenly dashes toward the soldiers. one of' b'the soldiers cannot manage to get away, they start stomping on him with their' b"feet, everyone's kicking him i become ill and go home, and explain in" b"general terms that horrible things are going on out there can't speak" b". well, they've probably killed that soldier, the way that crowd is b'if each of them kicked him just once they took his club away from him' b"and started to beat him with it. but it was far away and i couldn't see if he" b'got up and left or not.' b'' b'i become terrified and go home and say, "lyuda, don\'t go anywhere, stay at our' b'place, because if you go out they could kill you or then the crowd' b'runs over closer toward our building and stands at the 12-story building and' b'starts shouting something. we go out onto the balcony. all of our neighbors' b'are also out on theirs, too. everyone is standing, staring. the mob is' b'shouting and about minutes later comes running toward our building. as it' b'turns out, at the 12-story building the azerbaijani neighbors went down and' b"kept them from coming in. there's only one entryway there, they could stop" b'them.' b'' b'they all run up to our building. mamma immediately starts closing the windows,' b'afraid that they might throw stones. they have stones and they break the' b'windows, all of them. there are very many people. we have a large courtyard,' b"and it's packed with people. they spill up to the first floor so they don't" b"crush each other. they crawl up on trees, posts, and garages. it's just a huge" b'cloud of people. they break and burn the motorcycle of the armenian sergey' b'sargisian, from our building. we close the windows and immediately hear' b'tramping in our entryway. they come up to our fifth floor with a tremendous' b"din and roar. it's incomprehensible. mamma told me later that they were" b'shouting father\'s name, "grisha, open the door, we\'ve come to kill you!," or' b"something like that. i don't remember that, i was spaced out, kind of. mamma" b'says, "into the bedroom, quickly!" in the bedroom we have two tall beds, part' b'of our dowry; mamma says, "hide there, they probably won\'t come in there,' b'they\'ll ask something, say something, and leave." she says, "we\'ll tell them' b'that we live alone here." i can\'t imagine that my parents will stand out in' b'the hall alone talking with some sort of beasts i go to them and say' b"that i'll stand together with them, i'll talk with them if they come, maybe i" b'can find a common language with them, all the more so if they know me: i speak' b'azerbaijani more or less, and i can find out what they want. i told marina and' b"lyuda to hide under the bed, and my sister lyuda, i can't remember if i told" b'her anything or not.' b'' b"then they open the door: it's like they blew on it and it broke and fell" b'right into the hall. the crows bursts in and starts to shout: get out of here,' b'leave, vacate the apartment and go back to your armenia; things like that. i' b'tell them, "what has happened, speak calmly. one of you, tell me, calmly, what' b'has happened." in azerbaijani, they say, "get out of the apartment, leave." i' b'say, "ok. go downstairs. we\'ll gather everything we need and leave the' b'apartment." i realize that it is senseless to discuss any sort of rights with' b'them, these are animals. they must be stopped. the ones standing in the' b'doorway, the young guys, say, "there are old people and one girl with them.' b'too bad!" they take two or three steps back. it seems as though i have' b'pacified them with our exchange. then someone in the courtyard shouts,' b'commanding them: "don\'t you understand what you are saying? kill them?"' b'' b'and that was it! that was all it took. they grab papa, carry him into one' b'room, and mamma and me into another. they put mamma on the bed and start' b'undressing her, beating her legs. they start tearing my clothes, right there,' b"in front of mamma. i don't remember where they went, what they did, or how" b'much time passed. i had the feeling that they beat me on the head, on my body,' b"and tore my clothes, all at the same time, i don't even know what i said. the" b'atrocities started. i was savagely raped in that room. they argued among' b'themselves who would go first.' b'' b"later, i remember, i came to. i don't know if i'm dead or alive. someone comes" b'in, someone tall, i think, clean-shaven, in an eskimo dogskin coat, balding.' b"he looks around at what's happening. at that instant everything stops. it" b'seems to me that he is either their commander or that somehow everything' b'depends on him. he looks and says, "well, we\'re done here." they are beating' b'mamma on the head. they break up the chairs and beat her with the chair legs' b". she loses consciousness, and they decide that she's dead. papa was" b"out cold. they want to throw lyuda off the balcony, but they can't get the" b'window open. apparently the window frames are stuck after the rain and the' b"windows can't be opened. they leave her next to the window. she was thinking" b"about being thrown out the window and passed out. she's not a real strong" b"person anyway he looks at me and sees that i'm saying something, that" b"i'm still twitching. well, i start saying the opposite of what i should be," b'which is humbling myself and pleading. i start shouting, cursing they' b"don't get any entreaty out of me. i already know that i'm dead, why would i" b"humble myself before anyone? and he says that if that's what i think, since my" b'tongue is so long maybe he thinks that i still look quite appealing' b'. in short, he commands that i be taken outside.' b'' b"i no longer saw or remembered what was happening to marina and lyuda, i don't" b'know if they are alive or not. they take me outside. they are dragging me by' b'my arms, by my legs. they are hitting me against the wall, the railings,' b'something metal while they are carrying me someone is biting me, someone' b"else is pinching me .i don't even know. i think, my god, when will death" b'come? if only it were sooner then they carry me out, throw me near' b'the entryway and start kicking me. i lose consciousness what' b"happened after that, how many people there were, i don't remember." b'' b"i come to after a while, i don't remember how long. a neighbor is bringing me" b"clothing. i'm entirely covered with blood, she puts a dress on me. i remember" b'that i said the same words over and over again: "mamma, what happened, mamma,' b'what have they done to us, where are we, whose house are we at?" i can\'t make' b'sense out of anything. there is a guy standing over me, i sort of know him, he' b'served in afghanistan, his name is igor, he brought me indoors. when they all' b'went to the third entryway and killed a person there, igor gathered his' b"courage, took me into his arms, and brought me to the neighbors', even though" b"he's small