 b'back to our place and lay under the bed b'' b"i came to. mother was there. i can't remember my supervisor's telephone" b'number, but something had to be done. somehow i remembered and called, and he' b"came to get us. he didn't have any idea what was going on. he thought we were" b"simply afraid, he didn't know that they were killing us and that we had passed" b'between life and death. he came and got us and took us to the police precinct.' b'there they looked us over. i was having trouble walking, my lungs hurt badly,' b'it was hard to breathe b'' b"my supervisor's name is urshan feyruzovich mamedov. he's the head of our" b'administration. they took us there. when we were leaving, i saw a great number' b'of buses full of soldiers at the entrance to town. the buses were ordinary' b'passenger buses. there were very many soldiers. we left around eleven, right' b'after eleven. if these people could stop what was happening they could save a' b'great many lives because the crowd was moving on, toward the school, and' b'what was going on there i think everyone know not only in sumgait, not' b'only in yerevan. because there they murdered them all one after the next,' b'without stopping. after us.' b'' b'i think people died in microdistrict no. and to of them were from' b'buildings and in our building one person died, and one old woman died' b"from building that's the building in front of ours. there young" b"azerbaijani men stopped the mob and wouldn't let it into their building." b"incidentally, when we were at the neighbors', marina called our relatives" b'to warn them, so they would all know what was happening. i called a aunt in' b'microdistrict no. they have three neighbors who are armenians. i said, "run' b"quickly, i can't explain what's going on; hide, do what you can, just stay" b'alive. hide at azerbaijanis\', ones who won\'t give you away." at that moment' b'three people came in, policemen. i think they were azerbaijanis. i was in such' b'awful condition, my face was completely distorted my lips were puffed up,' b'there was blood, my eye was swollen, no one thought i would ever see anything' b'out of that eye again my forehead was badly cut, and one-half of my face' b'was pushed out forward. no one would have thought that i would survive, get my' b'normal appearance back, and be able to grasp anything at all. i started to' b'scream at those people, why did you come, who sent you here, no one wants you' b"here, haven't you killed people people yet, what are you doing here? one of" b'the soldiers said, "don\'t scream at us. we\'re muslims, but we\'re not from the' b'sumgait police. they called in from daghestan." so at that point the' b'daghestan police were there.' b'' b'when we got to the police precinct there were an awful lot of police there,' b"there were soldiers, police with dogs, ambulances, firemen i don't know," b'maybe they were waiting for people to bring them the goners and the seriously' b"injured to treat them there in the police precinct. i don't know what they" b'were there for. there were also doctors from baku there. they examined lyuda' b'and me and said, "these women need to go to the maternity home, but we don\'t' b'know what to do with the rest."' b'' b'so they took us, and i lost contact with my parents, my boss, everyone. my' b'boss said, "don\'t worry, i\'ll find you, no matter where you are, no matter' b'what happens." we went to the hospital. there we were examined by a department' b'head from the sumgait maternity home, pashayeva, i think her name was. she' b'examined us. the ambulance was from baku; i figured out that the sumgait' b"ambulances hadn't done anything, they didn't respond to any calls. people" b'called and neither the police nor the ambulances showed any sign of life.' b'' b'that doctor looked me over and i could tell from her behavior that something' b'very good had happened, for she became quite glad. i even thought to myself,' b'"god, can it be that nothing all that bad is wro