me. each day they came, showed' b'interest, and were constantly bringing me money. they did everything they' b"could. of course i'm most thankful to my boss, the only one of my colleagues" b"who didn't lose his presence of mind and who didn't change his opinions," b'neither before, nor after, nor in the heat of the moment, no matter what' b'happened. he constantly took an interest. a sincere interest, from the heart' b'. then, about two days later, the secretary of the party committee came,' b'not from our party organization, but from the first trust, which ours is part' b'of, comrade kerimov, a very important figure in our town. he made arrangements' b'with the emergency medical personnel to take me away, because if i sat down by' b"myself i couldn't get up or lie down again. there was something wrong with my" b'lungs, it was hard to breathe. they examined me there several times, there i' b'lay were several doctors, they all thought that that it must just be' b"from all the blows, i don't know. they didn't diagnose anything in particular." b'when i was in the maternity home i even asked i made it a point of' b'insisting that they take me to the trauma section because i felt so awful.' b"there was no way something inside wasn't broken, my ribs well they took" b'me there and took x-rays and said that everything was fine. there were' b"emergency medical workers on duty in the club. the mother of one of marina's" b"friends was there. she was the head doctor at the sumgait children's clinic." b'they had every kind of antifever agent in the world, which was exactly what i' b'needed at that moment, i thought. i said that i was having great difficulty' b"breathing, i couldn't seem to get enough air, something was wrong with me." b'they put tight bandages around my chest and waist. later i overheard some' b'people saying that i had been cut all over. i think they just saw me being all' b'bandaged up and decided that my breasts and face had been cut but i' b"wasn't cut." b'' b'they took us to the khimik boarding house. we lived there a long time. soon' b'appeared representatives they were agitating. at first people would not' b'talk to them, and drove them off. one of the armenian women shouted, "we' b'demand that seidov come!" the response was, "it\'s seidov who sent us." seidov' b'is the chairman of the azerbaijani council of ministers. the woman said,' b'"we\'ll only see seidov\'s daughter, have her come here, we\'ll do the same' b"things to her that they did to our daughters, and then we'll deal with you" b'agitators." and so on. more of them said, "have seidov himself come." this' b'went on day in, day out. the agitators kept coming and coming, this drove us' b'out of our wits. then people gradually started departing for yerevan because' b'they realized it was senseless to stay. everything got on our nerves: the' b'smell, the small children. there were children at the sk club, children who' b'had literally just come out of the maternity home. what were they doing in a' b"club that didn't even have running water all the time? at first we had to pay" b'to eat there. they even overcharged us, as it turned out. on the second day' b'someone told us that they would bring us food for free. the children were ill.' b'everything stank there. well imagine about people in a small movie' b"theater with seating for no more than you couldn't sit or lie down, it" b'was impossible to even move. the stench was awful. even the smallest infants' b'took ill overnight there. i heard that they were arriving seriously ill in' b'yerevan, the infants. they have to be washed, they have to be bathed, not to' b'mention that we, the adults, were ill and needed care. people were fainting' b"right and left. i just don't know, everyone was crying, everyone only" b'the young people, the men, somehow managed to keep it together. but the women' b'were in a constant state of panic. it seemed to everyone that they would come' b'any minute and kill and stab. it seemed clear that we had been gathered' b'together purposely, like during the war, so that they could burn the movie' b"theater and there wouldn't be a single armenian left. then people went up to" b"the attic. i didn't see them, i only heard them, because i was lying down and" b"couldn't get up. i lay right on the stage, we had some room there. apparently" b'they caught two people with either oil or gas. i think they wanted to burn the' b"theater. maybe someone saw them, i didn't. i was in no condition to open my" b'eyes.' b'' b'everyone was suspicious of everyone else. they would ask, "aren\'t you an' b'azerbaijani? i think i saw you somewhere, i think you\'re an azerbaijani." they' b'led out all the men and started letting them back in by checking their' b'passports, relatives might be covering for each other. half of the people did' b'not have any documents. there were people who had run out of their homes in' b'nothing but a pair of pants and slippers, or wearing just a shirt, not like' b'they should have, with their ids.' b'' b'so on the 28th, on sunday, i think, the police did nothing to help us. on' b"monday everything resumed where it had left off on block 41a. they didn't" b'spare a soul there: not children, not pregnant women, nobody. they killed,' b'they burned, they hacked with axes, just everything possible. they murdered' b'the melkumian family whom i knew, my mother worked with them. their daughter-' b'in-law went to school with my older sister. they were brutally murdered. only' b'the two daughters-in-law survived. by a miracle one was able to save herself,' b"she ran away, the neighbors wouldn't take her in, so she ran about the" b'building until she found refuge. she was pregnant and had two small children.' b'this all continued on monday in block 41a, on the 29th, when the troops were' b'already in the city.' b'' b'they murdered people, they overturned automobiles, and they burned entire' b"families. they say they didn't even know for sure if the people were armenians" b"or not. i heard that the lezgins suffered, too. i'm not sure myself, i didn't" b"see any lezgins who had been injured. they burned cars so it's very difficult" b"now to say exactly who died and who didn't. it was very difficult to identify" b'the corpses, or rather, what remained of the corpses after they were doused in' b"gasoline and burned it's all very hard to imagine, of course i heard" b'that many people disappeared without a trace, from the btz plant two people,' b'including a woman who worked the night shift, aunt razmella, who also lived in' b'microdistrict b'' b'they were stopping buses between baku and sumgait. in the evening people who' b'had been visiting baku were returning to sumgait, and people from baku were' b'going home from sumgait, and there were students, too. they were simply' b'savagely murdered. they were stopping the buses, the drivers immediately did' b'what they were told because there was just no other way to deal with that' b'hoard of brutally minded people. they stopped the buses, dragged the armenians' b"out and killed them on the spot. i didn't see it myself, but i heard that they" b'put them all in a pile so as to burn them. later it was hard to discern from' b"the corpses, well you can't call them corpses, you had to figure out from the" b'ashes who it was. l heard that two fellows saved two women, one a student, ira' b"g., if i'm not mistaken. she was in the hospital a long time after that, and" b"she still can't figure out who saved her. she was also brutally raped and" b'beaten and thrown onto a pile of corpses. the fellow pulled her out of that' b'whole pile of corpses, put his coat on her, took her into his arms, and' b"carried her to the city. i still can't imagine how he managed to do that." b'' b'i heard that from engels grigorian. he knows her, apparently. well a lot of' b'people went to that hospital anyway. she was in the hospital and singing a' b'song in armenian, and they wrote the words down, and, i